english:
  title: Fragrant Rice
  author: Sung Hyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Fresh spring warmth settles on Gyerim's outer fields,
    Emerald branches emerge at dawn near Heaven's Spring Pavilion.
    Before the pavilion, an old crow arrives—from where?
    Bearing sealed letters, conveying earnest intentions.

    A southern breeze draws in the young man,
    A dagger gleams within the zither's case.
    Returning with an arrow drawn, piercing through—
    One person survives, two fall dead.

    White rice mixed with sesame oil,
    Fragmented fruits steeped in honeyed brine,
    Steamed in jade vessels, fragrance rising thick—
    Yearly on the fifteenth day, an offering to crows,
    A sincere repayment of grace and debt,
    Surpassing even bells and drums in the royal presence.

    Once created as play, this exquisite taste
    Has passed down through generations to this day.
    In the mansions of nobles, competing in luxury,
    With slender jade fingers stirring the sacred rice,
    At dawn sealed and offered to the Nine-Fold Heaven,
    Distributed among the scholars of the royal academy.

    Yet I, born fallen and desolate, have forsaken fortune's blessing—
    Where I wander, bitter greens are my only sustenance.
    Suddenly, from a neighbor's hand, I taste one bowl,
    And my belly full, I forget the poverty of famine years.

    Fame and riches are but dreams within dreams,
    The distant isles fade, phoenixes and cranes beyond reach.
    I shall never taste again the celestial kitchen's fare,
    Only growing old in rough hemp robes, in this cold and hollow place.
  footnotes:
    - The 'old crow' likely references a legend of gratitude and spiritual communication in East Asian tradition.
    - The dagger and zither case incident appears to allude to a dramatic episode, possibly referencing historical or legendary events known to the original audience.
    - The fragrant rice (yakbap) was traditionally prepared as a refined delicacy for royal court and nobility in Joseon Korea.
    - The contrast between the imperial court's elaborate preparation and the poet's humble subsistence forms the philosophical core of the work.
